2 SENATE BILL 113
1 (2019 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
2 (As enacted by Chapters 33 and 34 of 2025)
3 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
4 Article – Human Services
5 Section 10–204, 10–206, and 10–208
6 Annotated Code of Maryland
7 (2019 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
8 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
9 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
10 Article – Human Services
11 10–101.
12 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
13 (b) “Area agency on aging” means the local agency that the Department
14 designates in accordance with the Older Americans Act of 1965 to administer the delivery
15 of a comprehensive and coordinated [plan] SYSTEM of social and other services and
16 activities for older adults in a planning and service area.
17 (c) “Community for a Lifetime” means a community certified under § 10–804 of
18 this title.
19 (d) “Department” means the Department of Aging.
20 (E) “LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN” MEANS A MULTISECTOR PLAN
21 ON AGING THAT:
22 (1) TRANSFORMS PROGRAMS, SERVICES, POLICIES, INSTITUTIONS,
23 AND SYSTEMS TO ADDRESS THE GROWING POPULATION OF OLDER ADULTS; AND
24 (2) INCORPORATES STREAMLINED, INNOVATIVE APPROACHES TO
25 AGING SERVICES.
26 [(e)] (F) “Planning and service area” means an area of the State that the
27 Department designates in accordance with the Older Americans Act of 1965 for the
28 planning and administration of social, health, and other services for older adults.
29 [(f)] (G) “Secretary” means the Secretary of Aging.
30 10–204.

SENATE BILL 113 3
1 (a) The Secretary shall administer the programs and activities that the federal
2 government delegates to the State under the Older Americans Act of 1965 that are not
3 otherwise committed by law to another unit of State government.
4 (b) The Secretary:
5 (1) is a member of the Governor’s Executive Council; and
6 (2) shall cooperate with and receive the cooperation of State, federal, and
7 local governmental units to carry out the purposes of this title.
8 (c) The Secretary shall LEAD IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LONGEVITY READY
9 MARYLAND PLAN, WITH THE FOLLOWING GOALS:
10 (1) BUILDING A LONGEVITY ECOSYSTEM;
11 (2) PROMOTING ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY;
12 (3) PREPARING STATE RESIDENTS TO AFFORD LONGEVITY; AND
13 (4) OPTIMIZING HEALTH, WELLNESS, AND MOBILITY.
14 (D) TO IMPLEMENT THE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN, THE
15 SECRETARY SHALL:
16 (1) evaluate the service needs of [seniors] OLDER ADULTS in the State;
17 (2) determine the extent to which existing public and private programs
18 [meet the needs of seniors], POLICIES, INSTITUTIONS, AND SYSTEMS SUPPORT OLDER
19 ADULTS;
20 (3) establish priorities for meeting the needs of [seniors] OLDER ADULTS;
21 AND
22 (4) coordinate, subject to existing law, assess and evaluate, and educate the
23 public and professionals about all State and local programs and services, both public and
24 private, that:
25 (I) relate and are important to the well–being of [seniors] OLDER
26 ADULTS in the State[, including programs and services in the areas of:
27 (i) income maintenance;
28 (ii) public health;

4 SENATE BILL 113
1 (iii) mental health;
2 (iv) housing and urban development;
3 (v) employment;
4 (vi) education;
5 (vii) recreation; and
6 (viii) rehabilitation of seniors with physical or mental disabilities; and
7 (5) develop a statewide plan incorporating local plans for a comprehensive
8 and coordinated system of health, social, and community services for seniors, including
9 housing, and institutional and noninstitutional care]; AND
10 (II) ARE DESIGNED TO ASSIST OLDER ADULTS AND FAMILY
11 CAREGIVERS IN LEADING INDEPENDENT AND DIGNIFIED LIVES IN THEIR OWN
12 HOMES AND COMMUNITIES.
13 [(d)] (E) The Secretary shall:
14 (1) represent the interests of [seniors] OLDER ADULTS by serving as an
15 advocate FOR POLICY, SYSTEMS, AND INSTITUTIONAL CHANGE at all levels of
16 government AND WITHIN THE PRIVATE SECTOR IN SUPPORT OF THE LONGEVITY
17 READY MARYLAND PLAN;
18 (2) [consult with and advise the secretaries of the principal departments of
19 State government] EMPHASIZE CROSS–SECTOR COLLABORATION, INCLUDING
20 CONSULTING AND ADVISING UNITS OF STATE GOVERNMENT AND STATE BOARDS
21 AND COMMISSIONS about [the programs and services for seniors that are the primary
22 responsibility of those departments] ANY ACTION THE UNIT, BOARD, OR COMMISSION
23 MAY TAKE TO ASSIST IN IMPLEMENTING THE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN;
24 (3) consult with the Commission on Aging on [all matters pertaining to
25 programs for seniors] IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND
26 PLAN;
27 (4) provide consultation and technical assistance to [communities and civic
28 groups] ORGANIZATIONS AND OTHER ENTITIES OR PERSONS developing local services
29 for [seniors] OLDER ADULTS IN PARTNERSHIP WITH AREA AGENCIES ON AGING AND
30 OTHER ORGANIZATIONS AND ENTITIES FUNDED BY THE DEPARTMENT;
31 (5) maintain a [clearinghouse of information] SYSTEM THAT PROVIDES
32 INFORMATION, REFERRALS, AND COUNSELING FOR OLDER ADULTS AND THEIR

SENATE BILL 113 5
1 CAREGIVERS related to the interests of [seniors] OLDER ADULTS AND THE
2 IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN; and
3 (6) review and recommend [policies] LEGISLATION AND OTHER POLICY
4 ACTION to the Governor on publicly funded plans [and], programs, INSTITUTIONS, AND
5 SYSTEMS that affect [seniors] OLDER ADULTS AND THE IMPLEMENTATION OF THE
6 LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN; AND
7 (7) MAINTAIN A PUBLICLY ACCESSIBLE RESOURCE ON THE
8 DEPARTMENT’S WEBSITE FOR MONITORING IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LONGEVITY
9 READY MARYLAND PLAN; AND
10 (8) INCORPORATE STRATEGIES INCLUDED IN PLANS DEVELOPED BY
11 LOCAL AREA AGENCIES ON AGING AND OTHER LOCAL ENTITIES.
12 [(e)] (F) The Secretary may adopt regulations to carry out the provisions of law
13 that are within the jurisdiction of the Secretary.
14 10–206.
15 (a) On or before January 1 each year, the Secretary shall report to the Governor
16 and, subject to § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, to the General Assembly ON:
17 (1) THE ALLOCATION OF FUNDS MADE AVAILABLE FOR SENIOR
18 CITIZEN ACTIVITIES CENTERS DISTRIBUTED BY THE DEPARTMENT; AND
19 (2) A SUMMARY OF KEY ACTIVITIES FUNDED AT SENIOR CITIZEN
20 ACTIVITIES CENTERS.
21 [(b) The report required under subsection (a) of this section that shall include:
22 (1) with the advice and recommendation of the Commission on Aging:
23 (i) a description of the senior citizen activities centers in each
24 county;
25 (ii) the allocation and use of funds made available for senior citizen
26 activities centers;
27 (iii) the results of any studies; and
28 (iv) any recommendations for legislation; and

6 SENATE BILL 113
1 (2) information regarding the operation and performance of accessible
2 housing services counseling provided by the Aging and Disability Resource Center
3 Program.]
4 (B) (1) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1 EACH YEAR, THE SECRETARY SHALL
5 REPORT TO THE GOVERNOR AND, SUBJECT TO § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
6 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY.
7 (2) THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
8 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE A SUMMARY OF:
9 (I) THE PROGRESS MADE DURING THE IMMEDIATELY
10 PRECEDING YEAR TO IMPLEMENT THE MOST RECENTLY PUBLISHED
11 COMPREHENSIVE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN;
12 (II) RECOMMENDATIONS FOR LEGISLATION, POLICY CHANGE,
13 OR OTHER RELATED PLANNING OR ADVOCACY EFFORTS MADE BY THE COMMISSION
14 ON AGING TO THE DEPARTMENT;
15 (III) ANY STUDY, SURVEY, OR OTHER FORM OF RESEARCH
16 CONDUCTED BY THE DEPARTMENT OR THE COMMISSION ON AGING; AND
17 (IV) ANY AVAILABLE RESEARCH AND BEST PRACTICES
18 REVIEWED BY THE COMMISSION ON AGING.
19 (C) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2029, AND EVERY 4 YEARS ON JULY 1
20 THEREAFTER, THE SECRETARY SHALL PROVIDE TO THE GOVERNOR AND, SUBJECT
21 TO § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY
22 AN UPDATED COMPREHENSIVE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN THAT:
23 (1) COMPLIES WITH § 10–204 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
24 (2) INCLUDES PROGRESS MADE ON EXISTING GOALS, OBJECTIVES,
25 AND STRATEGIES IDENTIFIED IN THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING LONGEVITY READY
26 MARYLAND PLAN;
27 (3) MAINTAINS EXISTING GOALS AND INCLUDES ANY ADDITIONAL
28 GOALS; AND
29 (4) UPDATES OBJECTIVES AND STRATEGIES IF APPROPRIATE BASED
30 ON EVOLVING CIRCUMSTANCES AND POPULATION PROJECTIONS; AND

SENATE BILL 113 7
1 (5) IS INFORMED BY THE STATE PLAN ON AGING AS REQUIRED BY
2 THE OLDER AMERICANS ACT OF 1965 AND OTHER RELEVANT STATE AND LOCAL
3 PLANS AND AGENCY COLLABORATIONS.
4 10–208.
5 (a) There is a Commission on Aging in the Department.
6 (b) (1) The Commission consists of [13] THE FOLLOWING members
7 [appointed by the Governor as follows]:
8 (i) [1 shall be a] ONE member of the Senate of Maryland, [who may
9 not vote] APPOINTED BY THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE;
10 (ii) [1 shall be a] ONE member of the [Maryland] House of
11 Delegates, [who may not vote] APPOINTED BY THE SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE; [and]
12 (iii) [11 shall be selected to reflect the geographic diversity of the
13 State and because of their interest in the needs of seniors] THE SECRETARY OF AGING,
14 OR THE SECRETARY’S DESIGNEE; AND
15 (IV) THE FOLLOWING MEMBERS, APPOINTED BY THE
16 GOVERNOR:
17 1. ONE DIRECTOR OF AN AREA AGENCY ON AGING,
18 SERVING AS THREE DIRECTORS OF AREA AGENCIES ON AGING, INCLUDING THE
19 PRESIDENT OF THE MARYLAND ASSOCIATION OF AREA AGENCIES ON AGING;
20 2. THREE REPRESENTATIVES OF ORGANIZATIONS
21 LOCATED IN THE STATE THAT ADVOCATE FOR OLDER ADULTS AND CAREGIVERS;
22 3. FIVE SIX EXPERTS ON AGING REPRESENTING THE
23 DISCIPLINES OF HEALTH CARE, TECHNOLOGY, ACADEMIA, INNOVATION, CONSUMER
24 PROTECTION, AND THE PRIVATE SECTOR AND PHILANTHROPY; AND
25 4. FIVE INDIVIDUALS WITH A DEMONSTRATED INTEREST
26 IN THE IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN; AND
27 5. ONE VETERAN WITH A DEMONSTRATED INTEREST IN
28 THE IMPLEMENTATION OF THE LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN.
29 (2) [At least 7 members shall be at least 55 years old] TO THE EXTENT
30 PRACTICABLE, COMMISSION MEMBERSHIP SHALL REFLECT THE AGE, RACE,
31 ETHNICITY, DISABILITY, GENDER IDENTITY, SEXUAL ORIENTATION, IMMIGRANT

8 SENATE BILL 113
1 HERITAGE, LIVED AND PROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE, AND REGIONAL GEOGRAPHIC
2 REPRESENTATION DIVERSITY OF THE STATE.
3 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE STAFF FOR THE COMMISSION.
4 [(c)] (D) (1) The term of a member of the Commission is 4 years.
5 (2) The terms of NEW members appointed under subsection [(b)(1)(iii)]
6 (B)(1)(IV) of this section are staggered as required by the terms provided for members of
7 the Commission on October 1, [2007] 2026.
8 (3) A member of the Commission appointed under subsection [(b)(1)(iii)]
9 (B)(1)(IV) of this section may not serve more than two consecutive terms.
10 (4) At the end of a term, a member continues to serve until a successor is
11 appointed and qualifies.
12 (5) A member who is appointed after a term has begun serves only for the
13 rest of the term and until a successor is appointed and qualifies.
14 (6) A MEMBER WHO FAILS TO ATTEND AT LEAST 50% OF THE
15 MEETINGS DURING ANY CONSECUTIVE 12–MONTH PERIOD SHALL BE CONSIDERED
16 TO HAVE RESIGNED.
17 (E) THE COMMISSION SHALL DETERMINE THE FREQUENCY, DATES, TIMES,
18 AND PLACES OF ITS MEETINGS.
19 [(d)] (F) (1) From among the members of the Commission, the [Governor]
20 SECRETARY:
21 (I) shall designate [a] THE chair OF THE COMMISSION; AND
22 (II) MAY DESIGNATE A VICE CHAIR OF THE COMMISSION.
23 (2) A MAJORITY OF THE MEMBERS THEN SERVING ON THE
24 COMMISSION IS A QUORUM.
25 (3) THE CHAIR MAY ESTABLISH SUBCOMMITTEES OF THE
26 COMMISSION.
27 (4) THE COMMISSION MAY CONSULT AND COLLABORATE WITH LOCAL
28 COMMISSIONS ON AGING.
29 [(e)] (G) A member of the Commission:

SENATE BILL 113 9
1 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Commission; but
2 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
3 Travel Regulations as provided in the State budget.
4 [(f)] (H) The Commission shall:
5 (1) exercise the powers and perform the duties specified in this title;
6 (2) [review:
7 (i) ongoing statewide programs and activities for seniors; and
8 (ii) new statewide programs for seniors before the programs are
9 implemented; and
10 (3) make recommendations to the Secretary about statewide programs and
11 activities for seniors] REVIEW AND ADVISE THE DEPARTMENT ON THE LONGEVITY
12 READY MARYLAND PLAN AND OVERALL PROGRESS OF THE DEPARTMENT AND
13 MULTISECTOR PARTNERS IN IMPLEMENTING THE RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE
14 MOST RECENTLY PUBLISHED LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN;
15 (3) ADVISE THE SECRETARY ON LEGISLATIVE, POLICY, AND OTHER
16 SYSTEMS CHANGES THAT COULD ASSIST WITH IMPLEMENTATION OF THE
17 LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLAN; AND
18 (4) ADVISE THE SECRETARY ON ANY UPDATE TO THE LONGEVITY
19 READY MARYLAND PLAN REQUIRED BY § 10–206 OF THIS SUBTITLE, INCLUDING
20 ANY UPDATE TO THE GOALS, OBJECTIVES, AND STRATEGIES TO BE INCLUDED IN
21 SUBSEQUENT LONGEVITY READY MARYLAND PLANS.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
23 (a) The terms of the members of the Commission on Aging serving on October 1,
24 2026, shall continue until the expiration of the member’s term.
25 (b) The terms of the members of the Commission on Aging appointed in
26 accordance with § 10–208(b)(1)(iv) of the Human Services Article, as enacted by Section 1
27 of this Act, shall expire as follows:
28 (1) four in 2028;
29 (2) five in 2029; and

10 SENATE BILL 113
1 (3) five in 2030.
2 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
3 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
